explore this extraordinary migration of Chinese Americans. Their exodus shaped Sino-American relations, the development of key economic sectors in China, the character of social life in its coastal cities, debates about the meaning of culture and “modernity” there, and the U.S. government’s approach to citizenship and expatriation in the interwar years. Spanning multiple fields, exploring numerous cities, and crisscrossing the Pacific Ocean, this book will appeal to anyone interested in Chinese history, international relations, immigration history, and Asian American studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mrz 2021) 0aChinese AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aChinese AmericanszChinay20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aborn in the usa.  achina.  achinese americans.  acoastal cities.  aemigration.  afleeing racism.  agovernment.  akey economic sectors in china.  amagnet for immigrants.  ameaning of culture.  amigration of chinese americans.  amoved to china.  arelocation.  asino american relations.  asocial life.  astruggling republic.  atottering empire.  aunited states.  aupward mobility.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052097255140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520972551423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520972551.jpg  a978-3-11-066763-9  UC Press eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles